        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>To achieve the scientific aims of this proposal we request sensitive mosaic observations of the central region of Westerlund 1 consisting of 27 pointings using Band 3. 
Our total time request as calculated by the Observing Tool is 3.61 hrs with 3.98 mins on source per pointing.

Sensitivity
The faintest radio observed OB star within Wd1 has an expected flux density of 0.06 mJy at 8.6 GHz (Dougherty et al. 2010, A&amp;A, 511, A58). Following the canonical model of S ~ v^0.6 expected for a smooth stellar wind gives a predicted flux of 0.26 mJy in ALMA Band 3.
The multi-waveband studies of wind structure suggest that the typical factor by which flux increases at mm wavelengths due to wind clumping is ~1.5. Knowing this clumping factor to within ~10-15% will significantly constrain models of the clumping factor as a function of wavelength. We therefore request a  1-sigma sensitivity limit of 0.03 mJy. This will provide around 7-10 sigma detections for an OB star enabling the required high level of constraint to accurately determine the appropriate clumping factor model.

Correlator setup
The proposed observations are sensitivity driven and require no spectral lines to be observed. As such, we request Time Domain Mode correlator setup with dual polarisation using the standard continuum-only setup for Band 3. 

Imaging
We request use of the extended array to provide high angular resolutions on similar scales to the previously published radio maps of Westerlund 1 (Dougherty et al. 2010, A\&amp;A, 511, A58), which will be used in conjunction with the observations proposed here. Extended emission has also been detected at lower radio frequencies of the order of 10-15\,arcsecs in size, which appears to be associated with hot dust within the cluster (Dougherty et al. 2010, A\&amp;A, 511, A58, Pg. 6). This extended emission should be well within the range of recoverable scales for Band 3 imaging.
The brightest radio-detected source in Wd 1 (W9) has an 8.6 GHz flux density of 24.9 mJy and a spectral index of 0.68. This will result in a predicted flux density in Band 3 of ~130 mJy. We will therefore require a signal-to-noise ratio of ~4000 to reach the level of constraint we require for the clumping factor models. 
To ensure we achieve the signal-to-noise we require, we propose to position W9 at the centre of one of the pointings for Wd1 in order to fully model the source and (if necessary) subtract the source from the field. 
The central coordinates of the rectangular region and the resulting pointings have therefore been chosen to position W9 at the centre of one of the pointings whilst covering the required field.

Calibration and bandpass accuracy
The science goals of this proposal can be achieved using standard observing and calibration procedures including standard calibration source observations. 

Scheduling/time constraints
None


Other Notes
We agree with the Cycle 1 panel comments regarding the preceding submission that we should initially concentrate on a single cluster to establish the technique and diagnostics. Wd1 was chosen since we have a wealth  of other multiwavelength data which we can  employ to fully utilise our requested ALMA observations. We believe Wd1 offers tremendous gain in terms of 
(i) the dramatically reduced time request with respect to observations of a comparable sample size of single stars,
(ii) the  well defined/understood nature of the physical properties of the sample
(iii) the well constrained age and distance/luminosity of the stellar sample within this massive cluster.
</prj:justificationText>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
